Incident.Summary: Theft of four wheeler and dirt bikes.

IncidentSuppNarrative.NarrativeTitle: Original Narrative
IncidentSuppNarrative.NarrativeText: Cpl. Slattery // Body worn camera Avaialable // Dash camera not available Attachments: MSP Form 67 Suspect: Unknown Victim: Brandon Keith Shores DOB: 05/01/1973 Statement: Shores advised he has a John Deere riding mower that is not functional and has been parked outside his garage. On February 1, 2023 Shores left for work at 0530 hours and, prior to leaving, he noticed the John Deere mower was not where it normally was. Shores stated that he was skeptical but decided to go about his day. Shores returned from work later that afternoon when he noticed several of his motion detecting lights had been knocked off of his garage. He then noticed the storage container on his property had been cut and he was able to freely open the door without having to undo his locks. Shores then stated he was missing two of his 4-wheelers and two dirt bikes. Shores also stated that he has two security cameras on the storage unit but they are fake and dont actually capture any footage. Shores advised one of his fake cameras had been moved so that it was not facing in the direction of the storage container door. Shores advised the last time he saw his John Deere mower was at 0200 hours on February 1, 2023 when he took his dog out. He assumes that the theft occurred between 0200 hours and 0530 hours on February 1, 2023 based on the movement of the mower. Scene Processing: I arrived on scene and noticed two lights that activate when they detect motion had been knocked off of their mounts and were laying on the ground. On the storage container there were two latches that were used to shut the container. Each latch contains a hole for the owner to use a pad lock in order to secure the door. The top latch had visible signs of manipulation and had been significantly bent. This indicated that the pad lock on the upper latch was not properly secured however, it still required manipulation by the suspect to gain access to the interior. The bottom lock had been properly secured. The hole on the storage container door had been fully cut so that the pad lock could be easily removed. Once both locks were removed, the door was easily opened. The fake security camera and a nearby floodlight had both been turned in a direction away from where the suspects would have been operating. There were tire marks in the gravel, seemingly from a 4-wheeler, that led away from the storage container and towards the end of the driveway. A small piece of broken ply wood was located in the driveway. Shores advised he did not know where it came from. It should be noted that in order to remove this large amount of property, a large truck or trailer would have been necessary. The ply wood could have been from a trailer or other piece of equipment used to haul the property away. I noticed an aluminum, red, Coca-Cola can just off of the driveway near the wood line and approximately 15 feet from the storage container. While there were no signs of recent use (Liquid or condensation) it appeared to be recently placed in that location. Shores also stated that he did not know where it came from. If empty, the can was too far away from the main road to have been thrown by a passerby. Given all the evidence, I made contact with Crime Scene Tech Kortchak who advised to collect the can and submit it for testing. I collected the can at approximately 1555 hours and confirmed by its weight that it was completely empty. The can was processed in conformance with MSP policy and procedure. Photographs of the scene were also taken and uploaded to Veripic. Neighborhood Check: As soon as I completed the initial scene processing, a serious injury collision was dispatched that occurred in my immediate area. Due to the crash, I was unable to conduct a proper neighborhood check. I was not able to return to the neighborhood at a reasonable hour and decided to conduct the neighborhood check on a future date. Narrative: On February 1, 2023 at approximately 1500 hours, I was dispatched to 13322 Catoctin Furnace Rd for a burglary. I arrived on scene and made contact with the victim, Brandon Shores, who made the above statement. While on scene, I conducted the above listed processing of the evidence and took several photographs. Shores identified the list of stolen property as the following: One white and red 2005 Yamaha Banshee 355 valued at $7,500.00 One green and black 2012 Kawasaki KFX 450 valued at $5,000.00 One green and black 2020 Kawasaki KX 100 valued at $3,500.00 One black and gray 2014 Honda Grom 125 valued at $3,000.00 One green and yellow 2008 John Deere riding mower valued at $750.00 Shores stated that all the paperwork he had for the stolen property was kept at an off site location making any identifying marks unavailable at the time of the initial investigation. Shores agreed to provide the information to me as soon as he has it. Any of the property with identifying numbers will be entered into METERS/NCIC as stolen and be searched through the RAPID database. Shores stated that he routinely fixes 4-wheelers and dirt bikes to sell them. Recently he sold a 4-wheeler to a man from southern MD. Shores indicated that he did not suspect him of the theft. Shores also advised that the 2005 Yamaha Banshee was listed on Facebook marketplace requesting a trade as compensation. I had Shores show me the listing and noticed that several of the other stolen property was visible in the photos he posted to Facebook Marketplace. It is also obvious, from the photos, that the property is in some type of storage container; although the exterior of the container is not shown. In the post, a potential buyer could easily discover the victims name, Brandon Shores, his general location, Thurmont, MD and several pieces of valuable property kept in a storage container. I conducted a google search of Brandon Shores Thurmont, MD. The second result was a link to a website Buildzoom.com. The link identifies Shores as an electrician with his business address as 13322 Catoctin Furnace Rd Thurmont, MD. It also should be noted that the storage container is easily visible from anyone driving by on Catoctin Furnace Rd. As stated, Shores intends to get serial numbers and further identifiers for his stolen property. At that time further investigation into the burglary will be conducted. All events occurred in Frederick County, MD I request this case remain open for further investigation.

IncidentSuppNarrative.NarrativeTitle: Supplement #1 Narrative
IncidentSuppNarrative.NarrativeText: I was equipped with a body worn camera. This incident was captured both audibly and visually. Narrative: On February 3, 2023, at approximately 1530 hours, I, TFC. Silver #6756 was dispatched to 13322 Catoctin Furnace Road, Thurmont, Maryland for a reported burglary. I arrived on scene and made contact with the complainant Brandon. Brandon advised that a trooper had just been there on February 1st for a reported burglary involving his storage trailer. I asked Brandon what happened he stated that his storage building had been broken into sometime between 0530 hours and 1500 hours when he was away at work. Brandon stated that he does not have any video surveillance cameras installed at his property. Brandon did not have the back door locked. I observed the backdoor to his property to not have a door knob or locking mechanism affixed to it. Brandon stated that he had placed two bike tires against it to keep it closed. Brandon stated that he noticed that his two Milwaukee Drill Sets were missing, but nothing else was taken. I asked Brandon if he had receipts or had any serial numbers for the items that were stolen, and he stated, No. Brandon stated that he did not realize when Cpl. Slattery arrived on February 1st that his two Craftsman generators were stolen as well, but he had forgotten to report them. All of these events did occur in Frederick County, Maryland. This concludes my involvement in Cpl. Slatterys investigation.

IncidentSuppNarrative.NarrativeTitle: Supplement #2 Narrative
IncidentSuppNarrative.NarrativeText: Cpl. Slattery // Body worn camera Available // In-car camera not available Narrative: On February 13, 2023, the victim, Brandon Shores, notified the MSP barrack that he had another burglary at his house. That burglary is captured under 23-MSP-005683 and was handled by TFC Dodson. On February 15, 2023, I conducted a neighborhood check of the area and the results are as follows: Tish Frederick (Across the street from Shoress residence) 13303 Catoctin Furnace Rd Thurmont, MD, 21788 Statement: Frederick stated that she did not see or hear anything during the burglaries. She did not have any recording equipment that could have captured anything. Haley Varner (Across the street from Shoress residence) 13319 Catoctin Furnace Rd Thurmont, MD, 21788 Statement: Varner stated that she did not see or hear anything during the burglaries. She did not have any recording equipment that could have captured anything. Ron Welsh (Across the street from Shoress residence) 13313 Catoctin Furnace Rd Thurmont, MD, 21788 Statement: Welsh stated that he did not see or hear anything during the burglaries. He did not have any recording equipment that could have captured anything. Welsh advised that he is retired and is home almost all the time. He works in his garage frequently at all hours of the night. He stated that he does not know Shores but sees all kinds of cars on his property. Welsh stated because there is no real pattern to the vehicles on Shores property, it is hard to notice if something was out of the ordinary. Robin Fritz (Next door, left of Shoress residence) 13320 Catoctin Furnace Rd Thurmont, MD, 21788 Statement: Fritz stated that she did not see or hear anything during the burglaries. She did not have any recording equipment that could have captured anything. It should be noted that there is no residence directly to the right of Shoress house. During the initial scene processing, a tire mark was seen in the mud that indicated the suspect vehicle either came from the North or left towards the North. Heading North on Catoctin Furnace from Shores house, there is no cross streets until Blue Mountain Rd. At the corner of Blue Mountain Rd and Catoctin Furnace Rd are two business, Affordable Glass and Portner Trucking. Employees at Affordable Glass looked into their recording cameras and later informed us that their cameras had not been recording for months and did not capture the date of the crime. I viewed cameras that Portner Trucking had from the date of the crime, but they did not provide anything substantial as the camera was directed towards their front gate making it difficult to view anything on Catoctin Furnace Rd. Narrative: On February 16, 2023, I made contact with Shores in reference to this case. I reminded him to get me any identifying numbers for his stolen property. He was only able to locate a VIN for the Honda as MLHJC6115E5007796. With the VIN, I was able to enter the Honda into the METERS/NCIC database as stolen. Shores also stated that he believes he has seen his property in Instagram videos authored by WheelieWayne whose real name is Dewayne Davis. Davis has a strong Instagram following and appears to be located out of Baltimore, MD. Shores also advised that he has joined a stolen motorbikes group on Facebook and now believes that his burglary is possibly part of a larger scheme across the state. Members of the group advised Shores that Cpl. Tilghman of the Maryland State Police CED has handled some of their cases, but Shores has not had any correspondence with Cpl. Tilghman. Given the seriousness of the crime, the prime suspect being located outside of Frederick County, and the possibility that this is part of a larger scheme, I request that this case and TFC Dodsons case (23-MSP-005686) be transferred to CED. All events occurred in Frederick County, MD

IncidentSuppNarrative.NarrativeTitle: Supplement #4 Narrative
IncidentSuppNarrative.NarrativeText: NARRATIVE: Throughout February 2023 I have stayed in contact with Cpl. Slattery in regard to this investigation as well as TFC Dodsons investigation, Case Number: 23-MSP-005683 On 2/28/2023, I contacted Cpl. Slattery in regard to the alleged suspect. I conducted a search of the suspect account through Instagram and did not observe any investigative leads into this case. Instagram Account: WheelieWayne appears to be an Instagram user that routinely violates traffic laws in Baltimore County, Maryland and records the actions for views. Speaking with Cpl. Slattery, Shores has identified multiple items to be his, and then retracts that the items are his when asked to confirm how he knows the items to be his. TFC Potvin has conducted searches through a law enforcement database as well as Facebook Martketplace for the black and gray 2014 Honda Grom 125 (VIN: MLHJC6115E5007796), with negative results. On 3/1/2023 at approximately 0937 hours, I contacted Cpl. Tilghman, of MSP CED, and discussed his investigation. During my communications, it did not appear that Cpl. Tilghmans investigation and this investigation were related. Cpl. Tilghman and I will be in communication if any true investigative leads are produced in either case. D/Sgt. Stein and Cpl. Slattery have been advised given the facts of the case and no true investigative leads to pursue in the case being present, that MSP CED - Western Region Investigators would not be pursuing the case any further and recommendations on case disposition have been provided.If investigative leads are provided, the Western Region Investigators will conduct further assistance/investigation into the case. This concludes CED Western Region Investigators involvement into the case.

IncidentSuppNarrative.NarrativeTitle: Supplement #5 Narrative
IncidentSuppNarrative.NarrativeText: Narrative: On February 25th, 2023 I was given a lab report in reference to the Coca Cola can left on scene of the initial burglary. Two latent prints and one swab of DNA were extracted from the can to be sent for testing at a later date. On February 28th, 2023, Cpl. Mills from CED made contact with me in reference to this case. Cpl. Mills advised that CED would not be taking the case at this time because it did not have any credible suspect leads. Cpl. Mills authored a supplement to this case and advised that it could be suspended due to lack of suspect information. The victim was given Cpl. Mills contact information and advised to contact him if he were to gather any leads at which time Cpl. Mills will reopen the case. All events occurred in Frederick County, MD I request this case be suspended lack of suspect leads.

T-Mobile provided that Telephone Number: (443) 680-2660 was assigned to MOBILE BEACON 2 located at 2419 Hartford Ave, Johnston, RI 02919 and Telephone Number: (443) 621-3169 was assigned to Christina Helmick located at 7609 Cypress Ave, Baltimore, MD 21224. After a review of the data provided from the T-Mobile Call Data Records (CDRs), neither Telephone Number: (443) 680-2660 nor Telephone Number: (443) 621-3169 appeared to be in the area of the crime scene between the date range of 01/30/2023 02/14/2023. On 3/20/2023 at approximately 0923 hours, I electronically submitted the MSP 98 MSP 98A, for the T-Mobile CDR Search Warrant, to Judge Solt. At approximately 1419 hours, I received the signed MSP 98 MSP 98A from Judge Solt. On 3/31/2023 at approximately 1110 hours, I was contacted by POFC Pizza and advised that the Charles County Sheriffs Office had conducted a search warrant on Herrons residence. POFC Pizza later provided Det. Bigelows, identified as the lead detective, contact information. At approximately 2002 hours, I made contact with Det. Bigelow. Det. Bigelow provided details about his investigation and advised that during the execution of the search warrant, no items/vehicles from this investigation were recovered at Herrons residence. Det. Bigelow provided that he had recovered Herrons Apple iPhone and would be executing a search warrant on the device in the coming days. Det. Bigelow provided that he would provide me with information from Herrons Apple iPhone at a later time. On 4/7/2023 at approximately 1734 hours,POFC Pizza provided that he had encounter Herron during an investigation where Herron was operating a motor vehicle with stolen plates.POFC Pizza provided that Herron was in possession of a phone, which Herron later identified to be his mothers, due tothe Charles County Sheriffs Office still being in possession of Herrons phone. The investigation is still ongoing. Case Status: OPEN

IncidentSuppNarrative.NarrativeTitle: Supplement #12 - CED West Investigation - T-Mobile Search Warrant Return
IncidentSuppNarrative.NarrativeText: ATTACHMENTS: - Copy ofT-Mobile Search Warrant Return - Copy of Application for Statement of Charges NARRATIVE: On 5/9/2023, I received T-Mobiles Search Warrant Return for T-Mobile Telephone Number: (443) 414-1533. T-Mobile provided that telephone number:(443) 414-1533 was assigned toChristina Helmick located at 7609 Cypress Ave, Baltimore, MD 21224. T-Mobile provided electronic data of CDR Mediation and Data Sessions. During a review of the CDR Mediations, through 1/30/2023 2/14/2023, telephone number:(443) 414-1533 appeared to be located predominately operating in Baltimore County, MD and Prince Georges County MD. Upon review of the Data Sessions, through 1/30/2023 2/14/2023, for telephone number:(443) 414-1533 appeared to predominately be operating in Baltimore County, MD. I conducted a search of Baltimore with over 268 points meeting that criteria, and a search of Highlandtown revealing 233 points meeting that criteria. A search of Dundalk revealed over 150 points. However, on 2/1/2023, the night of the crime, from 06:27:17 to 07:06:38 UTC hours,telephone number:(443) 414-1533 was being located in the area of36 Walnut St, Thurmont, MD 21788 (39.62434722, -77.4022361). It should be noted that after converting UTC to EST, the time is 2/1/2023 at 0127 to 0206 EST hours, which is the time that Shores provided Cpl. Slattery in his initial report of the suspected time of the crime. It should be noted that there were other various points provided in the Data Session coming back to other areas, for more details, please refer to the Case File. Below is a visual representation of the provided locations of activity provided by T-Mobile: base64," style="height:287px; margin:5px 10px; width:700px" /> base64," style="height:288px; margin:5px 10px; width:700px" /> On 5/11/2023, I emailed Det. Bigelow to see if he was currently in possession of the Apple iPhone 13 Midnight 128GB (S/N: DJVHMQ0JHQ IMEI: 354739185680688). Det. Biglow advised he did not have possession of theApple iPhone 13 Midnight 128GB (S/N: DJVHMQ0JHQ IMEI: 354739185680688), however the cellphone he was in possession of did have the telephone number:(443) 414-1533. On 5/12/2023 at approximately 1045 hours, I responded to the District Court Commissioners Office,7300 Marcies Choice Ln, Frederick, MD 21704, and filed an Application for Statement of Charges, requesting a warrant be issued chargingShawn Michael Herron (W/M 02/01/1997) with the following: 1 count of 2 3010 CR 6-203(a) **BURGLARY/2ND DEGREE/GENERAL** 1 count of 1 1136 CR 7-104 **THEFT: $1,500 TO UNDER $25,000** 1 count of 2 3040 CR 6-205(c) **BURGLARY-4TH DEGREE THEFT** At approximately 1210 hours, I was contacted by the Commissioners Office and advised that Arrest Warrant D111CR23001243 (Case Number: D220377710) had been issued for Herron charging him with 2nd and 4th Degree Burglary as well as Theft: $1,500 to $25,000. At approximately 2237 hours, I notified POFC Pizza of Herrons active arrest warrant. On 5/15/2023, I received a voicemail from Det. Bigelow advising he had conducted a search warrant on Herrons cellphone. I provided Det. Bigelow an image of the stolen Honda Grom that was previously sent by Herron on his Facebook Account. The case is remaining OPEN pending Herrons arrest. Case Status: OPEN

IncidentSuppNarrative.NarrativeTitle: Supplement #15 - CED West Investigation - July Update
IncidentSuppNarrative.NarrativeText: ATTACHMENTS: - Copy of MSP 98 MSP 98A - Copy of Meta Platforms, Inc. Subpoena - Copy ofMeta Platforms, Inc. Subpoena Compliance NARRATIVE: On 6/20/2023 at approximately 0845 hours, I received the signed MSP 98 MSP 98A for the Meta Platforms, Inc. (Facebook) search warrant. On 7/4/2023 at approximately 0906 hours, TFC Potvin #6852 and I responded to Herrons listed address through the Motor Vehicle Administration (MVA), 7609 Cypress Ave, Baltimore, MD 21224. While walking to the property, I observed a dark-colored Nissan 370Z with no registration which has been provided to be Herrons. I made contact with Christina Lynn Helmick (W/F 04/14/1976) and advised her of the active arrest warrant for her son, Shawn Michael Herron (W/M 02/01/1997). Helmick advised she was aware that Herron had an active arrest warrant, adding that he no longer resides at the residence. While speaking to Helmick, she freely and voluntarily invited TFC Potvin and I into her residence to show that Herron was not in the residence. TFC Potvin and I accepted the invitation into the residence. Helmick accompanied TFC Potvin and I into the residence and escorted us to the basement. Helmick advised when Herron lived at the residence, he would stay in the basement. While in the basement, I observed a bedroom style area, however the area did not appear to be lived in. Helmick advised that she believed that Herron was staying with an unknown girlfriend and did not have a way to contact him. Helmick confirmed Telephone Number: (443) 414-1533 was the number that she used to communicate with Herron, until his cell phone was seized by Charles County Sheriffs Office. Helmick also provided that Herron previously had dirt bike/ATV style vehicles on the property, adding that the vehicles would routinely get stolen. Helmick also provided that she was unsure of Herrons employment status, adding in the past Herron would receive vehicles, to her knowledge from auctions, and sell them. On 7/10/2023 at approximately 1249 hours, I authored a subpoena, to Meta Platforms, Inc. in regard to Facebook Account: https://www.facebook.com/runitup.shawn.7?mibextid=ZbWKwL, and electronically submitted the subpoena to the Frederick County States Attorneys Office for review and endorsement. On 7/11/2023 at approximately 0815 hours, I received the signed and endorsed Meta Platforms, Inc. subpoena, from the Frederick County States Attorneys Office. At approximately 1015 hours, I electronically submitted the signed and endorsed Meta Platforms, Inc. subpoena, requesting IP logins from 7/1/2023 - 7/10/2023 for Facebook Account: https://www.facebook.com/runitup.shawn.7?mibextid=ZbWKwL, to Meta Platforms, Inc, via the Facebook Law Enforcement Online Requests. The request was assigned Case #: 7944462. On 7/20/2023 at approximately 0959 hours, I contacted Mr. Santinis office to follow up with Herron turning himself in for the active arrest warrant. I was advised by the receptionist that Mr. Santini would contact me at his earliest convenience. At approximately 1114 hours, I received Meta Platforms, Inc. Subpoena Compliance for IP address logins for Facebook Account: https://www.facebook.com/runitup.shawn.7?mibextid=ZbWKwL. Meta Platforms, Inc. could not provided any IP logins for the requested date range. At approximately 1550 hours, I was contacted by Mr. Santini and advised that he has attempted to have Herron turn himself in, however even after being advised by his attorney, Herron still has not turned himself over to law enforcement. Mr. Santini provided his email address so that I could forward him the arrest warrant information. At approximately 1919 hours, I emailed Mr. Santini, via email address: rsantini@santinilegal.com, and provided him the identification information of Arrest Warrant D111CR23001243 (Case Number: D220377710). The case is remainingOPENpending Herrons arrest. Case Status:OPEN
